If you have tried all the commercially available products (such as pyrethrines derivatives and amitraz), I would recommend that you request your veterinarian to use injectable preparations (like Ivermectin) that are active against both external and internal parasites.
You can complement this with tick control measures such as rotational grazing, bush clearance and biological methods.
Dr Ngetich WyckliffDepartment of Veterinary Surgery, Theriogenology and Medicine, Egerton University.





****My 200 rabbits died all at once
I saw your write-up on death caused by contaminated maize. What can cause the death of over 200 rabbits, with the major symptom being jumping for a few minutes and then dropping dead. 
Adeyemi Adeniyi, Nigeria
The description you gave suggests sudden death with non-pathognomonic signs. For rabbits, sudden death can be caused by poisoning, fright/stresses (heart attack), gastro-intestinopathies or sudden change of environments.
Losing 200 rabbits at ago suggests that the group was exposed to things like contaminated feed, contagious microbial infection or sudden change of the status quo, for example, sudden too much noise, predators and releasing indoor rabbits to hot environment.



